<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Info.plist for openagent.app — the outer server application on macOS.

  Why the server now ships as an .app bundle instead of a bare CLI binary:

  macOS TCC (Accessibility, Screen Recording, Automation, etc.) keys each
  permission grant to the process's *responsible* identity. For a bare CLI
  binary without a bundle, TCC uses a path-based entry (``client_type=1``)
  that is pinned to the binary's cdhash — which changes on every openagent
  release because the Python bytecode and version string change. The
  effect observed on lyra-agent running v0.6.10 was:

    tccd: Failed to match existing code requirement for subject
      /Users/development/.local/bin/openagent and service
      kTCCServiceAccessibility
      identifier "com.openagent.server" and anchor apple generic and
      [...] leaf[subject.OU] = B4KWCQFY8V

  The stored DR was correct, but the cdhash pin invalidated the entry.
  Worse, because a stale entry existed, TCC refused to re-prompt, and the
  request was denied silently with authReason=5 — the user never saw a
  dialog and Privacy & Security → Accessibility showed no toggle to
  toggle.

  Wrapping openagent in an .app bundle with this Info.plist moves TCC to
  a bundle-based entry (``client_type=0``) keyed by ``CFBundleIdentifier``.
  The identifier is stable across releases (locked by ``codesign
  --identifier`` + matching Info.plist), so a grant granted once persists
  across every future update that keeps the same Team ID and bundle id.

  LSBackgroundOnly keeps openagent invisible to the user — no Dock icon,
  no menu bar — since it's a headless agent runtime that the user
  interacts with through Telegram / Discord / WebSocket clients, not via
  a GUI. The .app is strictly a TCC packaging concern.

  The computer-control MCP sidecar lives at
  ``Contents/MacOS/openagent-computer-control`` inside the same bundle —
  TCC attributes its requests to the parent .app via the responsible
  process chain, so it no longer needs its own .app wrapper.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>CFBundleIdentifier</key>
    <string>com.openagent.server</string>
    <key>CFBundleExecutable</key>
    <string>openagent</string>
    <key>CFBundleName</key>
    <string>OpenAgent</string>
    <key>CFBundleDisplayName</key>
    <string>OpenAgent</string>
    <key>CFBundleShortVersionString</key>
    <string>1.0</string>
    <key>CFBundleVersion</key>
    <string>1</string>
    <key>CFBundlePackageType</key>
    <string>APPL</string>
    <key>CFBundleSignature</key>
    <string>????</string>
    <key>CFBundleInfoDictionaryVersion</key>
    <string>6.0</string>
    <key>LSBackgroundOnly</key>
    <true/>
    <key>LSMinimumSystemVersion</key>
    <string>10.15</string>
    <key>NSAccessibilityUsageDescription</key>
    <string>OpenAgent needs Accessibility to simulate keyboard input and mouse clicks when the agent automates GUI applications on your behalf.</string>
    <key>NSScreenCaptureDescription</key>
    <string>OpenAgent needs Screen Recording to capture screenshots so the agent can see what's on your screen when you ask it to.</string>
    <key>NSAppleEventsUsageDescription</key>
    <string>OpenAgent may send Apple Events to control other applications when you ask it to automate them.</string>
</dict>
</plist>
